You are adding a follow-up commit to Task 9 of the Phase 2 workspace redesign plan. Code-quality reviewer flagged two issues; fix both in one commit.

## Working directory

`/Users/vpulim/dev/ai/ax-next/.worktrees/feat-phase-2-workspace-host-plugin`

Current HEAD: `e5ce135 feat(workspace-git-server): extract GitEngine from plugin-test-only`

## Fix 1 (Important): queues Map memory leak

**File:** `packages/workspace-git-server/src/client/git-engine.ts`

The per-workspace queue at line ~494 is `Map<string, Promise<unknown>>`. Today, `enqueue` adds entries but never removes them — after a workspace's ops fully settle, the settled Promise sits in the Map forever. For an engine that serves many workspaces over its lifetime, this is a slow leak.

**Fix shape** (mirror the cleanup pattern in `mirror-cache.ts`):

```ts
const enqueue = <T>(workspaceId: string, fn: () => Promise<T>): Promise<T> => {
  const tail = queues.get(workspaceId) ?? Promise.resolve();
  const next = tail.then(fn, fn);
  const tracked = next.then(() => undefined, () => undefined);
  queues.set(workspaceId, tracked);
  // Drop the entry once this tail settles IFF no later op chained onto it.
  void tracked.then(() => {
    if (queues.get(workspaceId) === tracked) queues.delete(workspaceId);
  });
  return next;
};
```

Key invariants:
- A new `enqueue` arriving BEFORE `tracked` settles still chains onto it (because `queues.set` happens synchronously before any await).
- After all ops on a workspaceId settle, the Map drops the entry.
- The cleanup checks `queues.get(workspaceId) === tracked` so a later op (which replaced the tail) doesn't get prematurely cleared.

## Fix 2 (Minor): dead `_mirror` parameter in `pushScratch`

**File:** `packages/workspace-git-server/src/client/git-engine.ts`

`pushScratch(remoteUrl, token, _mirror, scratch, parent)` at line ~323 has an unused `_mirror`. The original `plugin-test-only.ts:pushScratch` never used `state.mirror` either — it was dead in the original too. Remove the parameter.

Update the call site at line ~594 to drop the corresponding argument. Update the header comment at lines 41-42 to remove the `_mirror` apology.

## Tests

The existing 5 git-engine smoke tests should keep passing. Add ONE new test that proves the leak fix:

```ts
it('queues map drops entries after workspace ops settle', async () => {
  // ... boot server, build engine ...
  const wsId = 'ws-leak-check-test';
  await engine.apply(wsId, { changes: [...], parent: null });
  // Drain microtasks so the cleanup runs.
  await Promise.resolve();
  await Promise.resolve();
  // Inspect the engine's internal queues map. Either:
  //   (a) Add a debug-only `engineSize()` accessor on the engine, OR
  //   (b) Use a workspace ops sequence that proves the Map shrinks indirectly
  //       — e.g., via a memory snapshot / weakref. Approach (a) is simpler.
  // RECOMMEND (a): add a small `_internalQueueSize?(): number` method to GitEngine,
  // marked @internal in JSDoc and named with the leading underscore so it's
  // clearly a test seam. Document it as test-only.
});
```

If you go with approach (a), add the method in the GitEngine interface AND impl, with an `@internal` JSDoc tag.

If you want to avoid widening the public API, use a different strategy:
- Run a series of N applies for N distinct workspaceIds, drain microtasks, then trigger an apply for ONE more workspaceId — assert that engine state stays bounded by checking that `engine.shutdown()` settles all tails in O(1) time relative to N (i.e., the queue map is empty before shutdown). Or check this via a dedicated `_internalQueueSize` test seam.

**Recommend approach (a) with the `_internalQueueSize` test seam.** It's the smallest behavioral surface for the highest test value. Keep the method off the public docs (no README mention), and prefix with `_` to signal "do not call from production code."

## Commit

```
fix(workspace-git-server): drop settled queues + remove dead pushScratch param

Reviewer flagged two issues from Task 9's GitEngine extraction:

- The per-workspace queue Map grew unboundedly: every workspaceId we
  ever serviced stayed in the Map forever, even after its ops settled.
  Mirror the cleanup pattern from mirror-cache.ts: add a tail-settled
  cleanup that drops the entry iff no later op chained onto it.

- pushScratch took a `_mirror` parameter that was never read. Drop it
  along with its corresponding argument at the only call site.

Adds a test seam (`_internalQueueSize`, @internal) so the leak fix is
pinned by a regression test.
```

